<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="section-inner">
    <div class="section-num">09 — FAQ</div>
    <h2 class="section-title">Big Chill Repair FAQ</h2>

    <div class="faq-list">
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Where is Big Chill made?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Big Chill was founded in 2001 in Boulder, Colorado by Thom Gillespie and Margaret Carroll. The brand designs its appliances in Boulder and uses GE-sourced core mechanical components. The custom retro-styled exteriors are produced to Big Chill's specification with their signature powder coat colors applied in the manufacturing process.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Does Big Chill use GE parts inside?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Yes — Big Chill sources its core mechanical components from GE. This means the compressor, sealed system, defrost system, igniters, elements, temperature sensors, and control boards follow GE platform specifications with GE-level parts availability. Most Big Chill parts are available through standard US appliance supply channels within 24–48 hours, the same as GE parts.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">How do I clean Big Chill's powder coat finish?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Non-abrasive, pH-neutral cleaning agents only. No abrasive pads, no citrus-based cleaners, no vinegar solutions — all of these damage powder coat. Big Chill recommends a mild dish soap solution with a soft microfiber cloth for regular cleaning. For stubborn spots, a gentle non-abrasive kitchen cleaner like Bar Keepers Friend (liquid, not powder) applied with a microfiber cloth is appropriate. Avoid all spray-and-wipe products containing citric acid — they etch powder coat on contact.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">My Big Chill microwave has no power at all — what's wrong?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Almost certainly a door switch failure, not the magnetron. Big Chill microwaves use a three-switch door circuit (primary, secondary, monitor) in series — when any switch fails, the circuit breaks and the microwave loses all power. This is the most common Big Chill microwave failure. We test all three door switches before any other component on a "no power" call. Door switch replacement is significantly less expensive than magnetron replacement and is same-day in most cases.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">What is the difference between Big Chill Classic and Big Chill Pro?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Big Chill Classic is the original retro line — rounded 1950s-inspired styling in 30" and 36" configurations, available in 37+ colors. Big Chill Pro takes the same aesthetic with higher BTU burners, larger oven capacity, and a more professional specification. Both use GE-sourced components and are available in the full color palette. Service protocols are identical.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">How does Big Chill compare to Elmira Stove Works?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Both make retro-styled appliances with modern internals. Key differences: Big Chill uses GE components (faster US parts availability) while Elmira uses various suppliers with some Canadian-specific parts. Big Chill has a broader color palette (37+ vs Elmira's curated selection). Big Chill is Colorado-based; Elmira is Ontario-based. Both use durable exterior finishes requiring non-abrasive care. We service both and can advise on mixed-brand retro kitchen maintenance when needed.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

